#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:56
msgid "Welcome to Godot"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:57
msgid "LET'S GET STARTED!"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:59
msgid "In this tour, you take your first steps in the [b]Godot editor[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:62
msgid "You get an overview of the engine's four pillars: [b]Scenes[/b], [b]Nodes[/b], [b]Scripts[/b], and [b]Signals[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:65
msgid "In the next tour, you'll get to assemble your first game from premade parts and put all this into practice."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:71
msgid "Congratulations on your first Godot Tour!"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:72
msgid "CONTINUE LEARNING ON GDSCHOOL"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:74
msgid "That's it for your first steps with the Godot editor. Ready to keep learning?"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:77
msgid "If you haven't already, check out the free app [color=#ffd500][b][url=https://gdquest.com/tutorial/godot/learning-paths/learn-gdscript-from-zero/]Learn GDScript from Zero[/url][/b][/color]. It teaches you the basics of coding through 20+ lessons with dozens of interactive exercises where you can immediately practice what you've learned."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:78
msgid "You can also explore our courses to [color=#ffd500][b][url=https://school.gdquest.com/products/godot-4-early-access]Pick Up Gamedev From Zero[/url][/b][/color], which offer a comprehensive path to build a game developer's mindset and become independent."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:81
msgid "I hope to see you around the GDQuest community!"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:97
msgid "Try the game"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:100
msgid "When a project is first opened in Godot, we land on the [b]Main Scene[/b]. It is the entry point of a Godot game."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:101
msgid "Click the play icon in the top right of the editor to run the Godot project."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:102
msgid "Then, press [b]%s[/b] on your keyboard or close the game window to stop the game."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:110
msgid "Editor tour"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:112
msgid "Great! Now let's take a quick tour of the editor."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:130
msgid "The viewport"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:132
msgid "The central part of the editor outlined in purple is the viewport. It's a view of the currently open [b]scene[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:138
msgid "A scene is a reusable template"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:141
msgid "In Godot, a scene is a template that can represent anything: A character, a chest, an entire level, a menu, or even a complete game!"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:142
msgid "We are currently looking at a scene file called [b]%s[/b]. This scene consists of a complete game."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:158
msgid "Let's look around"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:160
msgid "We're going to explore the interface next, so you get a good feel for it."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:168
msgid "Runner Buttons"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:169
msgid "Those buttons in the top-right are the Runner Buttons. You can [b]play[/b] and [b]stop[/b] the game with them."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:176
msgid "Context Switcher"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:179
msgid "Centered at the top of the editor, you find the Godot [b]Context Switcher[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:180
msgid "You can change between the different [b]Editor[/b] views here. We are currently on the [b]2D View[/b]. Later, we will switch to the [b]Script Editor[/b]!"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:190
msgid "Scene Dock"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:193
msgid "At the top-left, you have the [b]Scene Dock[/b]. You can see all the building blocks of a scene here."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:194
msgid "In Godot, these building blocks are called [b]nodes[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:195
msgid "A scene is made up of one or more nodes."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:196
msgid "There are nodes to draw images, play sounds, design animations, and more."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:204
msgid "FileSystem Dock"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:205
msgid "At the bottom-left, you can see the [b]FileSystem Dock[/b]. It lists all the files used in your project (all the scenes, images, scripts...)."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:212
msgid "The Inspector"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:215
msgid "On the right, we have the [b]Inspector Dock[/b]. In this dock, you can view and edit the properties of selected nodes."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:229
msgid "Try the Inspector"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:232
msgid "Try the [b]Inspector[/b]! Click on the different nodes in the [b]Scene Dock[/b] on the left to see their properties in the [b]Inspector[/b] on the right."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:252
msgid "The Bottom Panels"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:255
msgid "At the bottom, you'll find editors like the [b]Output[/b] and [b]Debugger[/b] panels."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:256
msgid "That's where you'll edit animations, write visual effects code (shaders), and more."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:257
msgid "These editors are contextual. We'll see what that means in the next tour."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:270
msgid "The complete scene's nodes"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:273
msgid "This completed game scene has four [b]nodes[/b]: [b]Main[/b], [b]Bridges[/b], [b]InvisibleWalls[/b], and [b]UILayer[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:274
msgid "We can see that in the [b]Scene Dock[/b] at the top-left."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:282
msgid "Scene instances"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:285
msgid "Other elements, like the [b]Player[/b], have an [b]Open In Editor[/b] %s icon."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:286
msgid "When you see this icon, you are looking at a [b]scene instance[/b]. It's a copy of another scene. You can think of it as a scene that uses another scene as its template. In Godot, we nest scene instances to create complete games."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:287
msgid "Click the [b]Open in Editor[/b] %s icon next to the [b]Player[/b] node in the [b]Scene Dock[/b] to open the Player scene."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:291
msgid "Open the Player scene."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:307
msgid "The Player scene"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:310
msgid "When opening a scene, the [b]Scene Dock[/b] and the viewport update to display the scene's contents."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:311
msgid "In the Scene Dock at the top-left, you can see all the nodes that form the player's character."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:323
msgid "Scripts bring nodes to life"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:326
msgid "By themselves, nodes and scenes don't interact."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:327
msgid "To bring them to life, you need to give them instructions by writing code in a script and connecting it to the node or scene."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:328
msgid "Let's have a look at an example of a script."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:336
msgid "Open the Player script"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:339
msgid "The [b]Player[/b] node has a script file attached to it. We can see this thanks to the [b]Attached Script[/b] %s icon located to the right of the node in the [b]Scene Dock[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:340
msgid "Click the script icon to open the [b]Player Script[/b] in the [b]Script Editor[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:344
msgid "Open the script attached to the [b]Player[/b] node."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:357
msgid "The scripting context"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:360
msgid "We're now in the scripting context, which displays all the code in the open script file."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:361
msgid "This code gives instructions to the computer about how to move the character, when to play sounds, and more."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:362
msgid "Don't worry if you can't read the code yet: We made a FREE app to help you [color=#ffd500][b][url=https://gdquest.com/tutorial/godot/learning-paths/learn-gdscript-from-zero/]Learn GDScript from Zero[/url][/b][/color]. It's a free part of our complete course Learn Gamedev From Zero."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:363
msgid "Use your [b]Mouse Wheel[/b] to scroll up and down the file or click and drag the scrollbar on the right."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:371
msgid "Any node can have a script"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:374
msgid "If we look back at the [b]Scene Dock[/b] at the top-left, we can see multiple nodes with script icons."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:375
msgid "You can attach scripts to as many nodes as you need to control their behavior."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:390
msgid "Go back to the 2D view"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:393
msgid "We have one more essential pillar of Godot to look at: [b]Signals[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:394
msgid "Let's head back to the completed project scene. First, click the 2D workspace at the top of the editor to change the center view back to the viewport."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:395
msgid "This will show you the player character once again."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:399
msgid "Navigate to the [b]2D[/b] view."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:410
msgid "Change the active scene"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:413
msgid "Let's change the active scene to the completed project scene."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:414
msgid "Click on the [b]completed_project[/b] tab above the central viewport to change the scene."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:418
msgid "Navigate to the Completed Project scene."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:432
msgid "Signals"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:435
msgid "Games have buttons, doors, chests and a myriad of other elements you interact with and that you expect to respond in a specific way."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:436
msgid "To do what you need them to do, these elements need to report events to the game to trigger the action you expect them to trigger."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:437
msgid "We call that a signal."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:446
msgid "Click the signal icon"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:449
msgid "In the [b]Scene Dock[/b] at the top-left, look at the [b]Player[/b] node."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:450
msgid "You can see the [b]Signal Emission[/b] %s icon emitting little waves. This icon tells you that the node has a signal connection."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:451
msgid "Click the icon to open the [b]Signals Dock[/b] at the right of the editor."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:454
msgid "Click the signal emission icon next to the [b]Player[/b] node and open the [b]Signals Dock[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:460
msgid "The Signals Dock"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:463
msgid "On the right, you can see the [b]Signals Dock[/b]. It lists all the signals of the selected node. In this case, it's the [b]Player[/b] node."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:464
msgid "The signal list is long: nodes emit many signals, because there are many kinds of events we need to react to in a game."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:472
msgid "The health_changed signal"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:475
msgid "The player node has one especially useful signal: [b]health_changed[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:476
msgid "The [b]health_changed[/b] signal tells us when the player takes damage or heals up."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:485
msgid "The signal connection"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:488
msgid "Notice the [b]Connected Signal[/b] %s icon below the signal: it shows that the signal is connected to a piece of code."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:489
msgid "It means that each time the player health changes, Godot will run the connected piece of code."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:490
msgid "We can double-click the line with the green icon to open the connected piece of code."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:494
msgid "Double-click the signal connection in the Signals dock."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:507
msgid "The connected code"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:510
msgid "The script editor reopens and focuses the view on the [b]set_health[/b] function."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:511
msgid "A function is a name we give to multiple lines of code for easy reuse: in other game code, we can then use the function name to execute all the lines of code in the function."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:521
msgid "The set_health function"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:524
msgid "This function updates the display of the player health bar."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:525
msgid "Notice the green [b]Connected Signal[/b] %s icon in the left margin of the script editor. When coding a game, it reminds you of existing signal connections."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:526
msgid "So, each time the player health changes, the [b]Player[/b] node emits the [b]health_changed[/b] signal and, in turn, Godot runs the [b]set_health[/b] function that updates the health bar in the running game."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:535
msgid "Run the game"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:538
msgid "Run the game again and pay attention to the health bar in the top-left."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:539
msgid "Move the player character to an enemy and touch them to lose health. You will see the health bar lose one point."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:540
msgid "This happens thanks to the [b]health_changed[/b] signal connection."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:552
msgid "In summary"
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:555
msgid "Godot has four essential concepts on which your games rely: scenes, nodes, scripts, and signals."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:556
msgid "[b]Scenes[/b] are reusable templates that represent anything in your game."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:557
msgid "[b]Nodes[/b] are the building blocks of scenes. They are the elements you see in the viewport."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:558
msgid "[b]Scripts[/b] are text files that give instructions to the computer. You can attach them to nodes to control their behavior."
msgstr ""

#: tours/101_the_godot_editor/101_the_godot_editor.gd:559
msgid "And [b]Signals[/b] are events that nodes emit to report what's happening in the game. You can connect signals to scripts to run code when an event occurs."
msgstr ""
